The Spring School 2019 on Models and Data took place at the University of South Carolina from 17th to 20th of March 2019. It was hosted by the Center on Data Analysis, Simulation, Imaging and Visualization (DASIV) in Sumwalt College. The sponsors of the event were the DASIV SmartState Center and the National Science Foundation.



The Spring School featured five main lecturers who are considered high-caliber representatives of their respective area of expertise and presented lectures on topics from these areas:

Albert Cohen (Sorbonne Universit?) on Least-Squares Methods for High Dimensional Problems;

Ronald DeVore (Texas A&amp;M University) on An Overview of Approximation of Functions of Many Variables;

Gitta Kutyniok (Technische Universit?t Berlin) on Theory of Deep Learning;

Eitan Tadmor (University of Maryland) on Collective dynamics: emergent behavior with long-range and short-range interactions;

Changhui Tan (University of South Carolina) on Asymptotic Preserving Schemes on Kinetic Models with Singular Limits.



In addition, three of the postdoctoral participants in the Spring School had the opportunity to present their research in half-an-hour lectures:

Simone Brugiapaglia (Simon Frasier University) on Compressive Sensing Approaches for High-Dimensional Function Approximation;

Qingguang Guan (Missouri University of Science and Technology) on Poor Global Optima for Fully Connected Deep ReLU Neural Networks - Special Examples for HD Approximation;

Majid Noroozi (University of Central Florida) on Clustering in Popularity Adjusted Stochastic Block Model.



The interactive lectures covered a diversity of topics organized under the main theme, namely, to foster synergetic synthesis of on the one hand classical "model-based" and, on the other hand "data-driven" methodologies. The topics addressed in the Spring Schools pertain to ongoing vibrant developments in areas like machine learning, notable deep learning, computational harmonic analysis, as a pillar of data science, or uncertainty quantification and related modelling or numerical analysis aspects.

The topics concern several relevant areas in Data Science which is an emerging transdisciplinary scientific field or research. The mathematical concepts treated in lectures and discussions are therefore relevant for a large range of disciplines where data in combination with physical/mathematical models provide major sources of information.



A total of 28 young researchers (students and postdocs) attended the Spring School: 12 from University of South Carolina, 3 from University of Pittsburg, 2 from Auburn University, 2 from University of Central Florida, 2 from University of Iowa, 1 from Florida State University, 1 from Missouri University of Science and Technology, 1 from Simon Fraser University, 1 from Southern Illinois University, 1 from Texas A&amp;M University, 1 from University of Georgia, and 1 from University of Louisville. In addition, 11 faculty from University of South Carolina attended some or all of the lectures.



All lectures and presentations were recorded and are posted on the DASIV website:

https://people.math.sc.edu/imi/dasiv/SpringSchool/2019/



